stylometry: When analyzing an @RISK output some of the things you will have to look at are the mean, standard deviation, minimum, maximum, etc. (you can also add different factors to be analyzed). With a simulation where your profit can vary a lot due to different demand or costs, looking at the mean is very important as this can indicate where the estimated average is of the spreadsheet. Also, looking at the standard deviation would help show you how well the data is being represented in the spreadsheet (too high may mean the data is too varied). Depending on what kind of problem you are working on, the other factors (minimum, maximum) may also be analyzed to determine the strength of the model and the risks associated with it.
